Loading, partitioning data

library(magrittr)
library(ggplot2)
library(lattice)

set.seed(12)
telecom <- readr::read_csv(
  file = "/Users/thienpham/Data Mining/data/prepared_telecom.csv",
  col_types = "cnnnnnnncnnnnnnnnnnnnnn"
) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    partition = ifelse(runif(dplyr::n()) > 0.15,"Train","Test")
  ) %>%
  as.data.frame()

Training a stochastic gradient boost model

pred_name <- c("tenure", "PhoneService", "Contract", "PaperlessBilling", 
               "PaymentMethod", "MonthlyCharges", "gender", 
               "SeniorCitizen", "Partner", "Dependents", "MultipleLines", 
               "InternetService", "OnlineSecurity", "OnlineBackup", "DeviceProtection", 
               "TechSupport", "StreamingTV", "StreamingMovies")
set.seed(
  seed = 12
)
sgb <- gbm::gbm(
  formula = target ~.,
  distribution = "bernoulli",
  data = telecom %>%
    dplyr::filter(partition == "Train") %>%
    dplyr::select(tidyselect::any_of(c(
      "target",pred_name
    ))),
  n.trees = 150,
  interaction.depth = 3,
  shrinkage = 0.1,
  n.minobsinnode = 10
)
sgb
## gbm::gbm(formula = target ~ ., distribution = "bernoulli", data = telecom %>% 
##     dplyr::filter(partition == "Train") %>% dplyr::select(tidyselect::any_of(c("target", 
##     pred_name))), n.trees = 150, interaction.depth = 3, n.minobsinnode = 10, 
##     shrinkage = 0.1)
## A gradient boosted model with bernoulli loss function.
## 150 iterations were performed.
## There were 18 predictors of which 18 had non-zero influence.

All 18 predictors were used which is a good thing. Any that were not used should be removed and refitted.

Obtaining optimal number of trees

gbm::gbm.perf(
  object = sgb,
  oobag.curve = TRUE
)
## OOB generally underestimates the optimal number of iterations although predictive performance is reasonably competitive. Using cv_folds>1 when calling gbm usually results in improved predictive performance.

## [1] 47
## attr(,"smoother")
## Call:
## loess(formula = object$oobag.improve ~ x, enp.target = min(max(4, 
##     length(x)/10), 50))
## 
## Number of Observations: 150 
## Equivalent Number of Parameters: 12 
## Residual Standard Error: 0.00057

We see that the optimal number of iterations is roughly 50. This means we should refit with 50 trees.

Refiting model with 50 trees

sgb8 <- gbm::gbm(
  formula = target ~.,
  distribution = "bernoulli",
  data = telecom %>%
    dplyr::filter(partition == "Train") %>%
    dplyr::select(tidyselect::any_of(c(
      "target",pred_name2[-c(2,7,9,8,13)]
    ))),
  n.trees = 50,
  interaction.depth = 3,
  shrinkage = 0.1,
  n.minobsinnode = 10
)
gbm::gbm.perf(
  object = sgb8,
  oobag.curve = TRUE
)
## OOB generally underestimates the optimal number of iterations although predictive performance is reasonably competitive. Using cv_folds>1 when calling gbm usually results in improved predictive performance.

## [1] 44
## attr(,"smoother")
## Call:
## loess(formula = object$oobag.improve ~ x, enp.target = min(max(4, 
##     length(x)/10), 50))
## 
## Number of Observations: 50 
## Equivalent Number of Parameters: 4.5 
## Residual Standard Error: 0.0011
telecom$predict <- predict(
  object = sgb8,
  newdata = telecom,
  type = "response"
)
## Using 50 trees...
residuals <- telecom$target - telecom$predict

rse <- sqrt(sum(residuals^2) / (length(residuals) - length(sgb8$coef)))
rse
## [1] 0.36

The standard error on our test set (0.36) is a lot worse compared to training statistics (0.0011). The following graph compares the visual accuracy of both set.

gbm::calibrate.plot(
  y = telecom %>%
    dplyr::filter(partition == "Train") %>%
    dplyr::pull(target),
  p = telecom %>%
    dplyr::filter(partition == "Train") %>%
    dplyr::pull(predict)  
)

gbm::calibrate.plot(
  y = telecom %>%
    dplyr::filter(partition == "Test") %>%
    dplyr::pull(target),
  p = telecom %>%
    dplyr::filter(partition == "Test") %>%
    dplyr::pull(predict)  
)
